Explanation:

I examined the route and controller code to determine what the POST /api/orders endpoint expects in the request. Relevant points:

- routes/orderRoutes.js maps POST /api/orders to protect, addOrderItems.
- protect middleware reads the JWT from a cookie named "jwt" and sets req.user; authentication is performed via a cookie. Swagger 2.0 does not have an official "in: cookie" parameter type, so I did not model the cookie auth as a parameter here (authentication is normally modeled in Swagger 2.0 via securityDefinitions, not as a path parameter).
- controllers/orderController.addOrderItems reads req.body and expects at least:
  - orderItems: an array. The code checks if orderItems exists and if its length is 0; if it is empty it returns 400. Each item must contain an _id (which the controller uses to look up the product in DB) and qty at minimum. The controller then uses the product records from the DB to set the canonical price and sets product to the provided _id.
  - shippingAddress: an object used directly when creating the Order. The Order model requires shippingAddress.address, shippingAddress.city, shippingAddress.postalCode, shippingAddress.country.
  - paymentMethod: a string.
- The controller ignores client-supplied price values for trust/security reasons (it replaces prices using DB values), but clients may still supply price fields; the schema below marks price optional and notes that server uses DB price.
- Because this is a POST with a JSON body, in Swagger 2.0 this is represented as a single body parameter with a schema. I built a Parameter Object for the request body describing the expected structure, with required fields per the controller and Mongoose schema.

